Build Models

From the analysis above, here are some information that help me build my model: 1.There are interactions between some of regions and bornUK, over65, Wealth respectfully. 2.over65 have non-linear relationship with BL(Brexit Leave) 3. large percentage of born UK have close linear relationship with BL

based on the information above, after finding non-linear relationships, I use plots of polynomial fit to check if each predictor has virtually fit well with data(Loess as reference), if the trend of polynomial fit is very close, I will choose that polynomial as my candidate model. after checking interaction between variables by ggplot, I add interaction to see if the interaction influence my models. I use AIC and F hypothesis test to pick the best model, The smaller AIC, the model have more good balance between complexity and residual.

I finally get three models that i think that are best three.

Model1 \[E[\verb|Brexit_Leave||\verb|over65,wealth,BornUk,Region|]=\alpha_0 + \alpha_1 \,\verb|over65|+\alpha_2 \,\verb|over65^2|+\alpha_3 \,\verb|Wealth|+\alpha_4 \,\verb|BornUK|+\alpha_5 \,\verb|Region|\] Model2 \[E[\verb|Brexit_Leave||\verb|over65,wealth,BornUk,Region|]=\gamma_0 + \gamma_1 \,\verb|over65|+\gamma_2 \,\verb|over65^2|+\gamma_3 \,\verb|Wealth|+\gamma_4 \,\verb|BornUK|+\gamma_5 \,\verb|Region|+\gamma_6 \,\verb|Region*over65^2|\] Model3 \[E[\verb|Brexit_Leave||\verb|over65,wealth,BornUk,Region|]=\beta_0 + \beta_1 \,\verb|over65|+\beta_2 \,\verb|over65^2|+\beta_3 \,\verb|Wealth|+\beta_4 \,\verb|BornUK|+\beta_5 \,\verb|Region|+\beta_6 \,\verb|Region*Wealth|+\beta_7 \,\verb|BornUk*Wealth|\]

Here is the AIC results of three models

mod1 <- lm(BREXITLeave~over65+Wealth+BornUK+Region+I(over65^2),brexit)

mod2 <-lm(BREXITLeave~over65+Wealth+BornUK+Region*I(over65^2),brexit)

mod3 <- lm(BREXITLeave~over65+I(over65^2)+Wealth+BornUK+Region+Wealth*BornUK+Wealth*Region,brexit)

cat("AIC of Model1:",extractAIC(mod1)[2],"\n")
## AIC of Model1: 1985.909
cat("AIC of Model2:",extractAIC(mod2)[2],"\n")
## AIC of Model2: 1981.837
cat("AIC of Model3:",extractAIC(mod3)[2],"\n")
## AIC of Model3: 1968.26

Hypothesis Test for my Model1: \[H_0:\, \alpha_0=\alpha_1=\alpha_2=\alpha_3=\alpha_4=\alpha_5=0 \qquad \mbox{vs} \qquad H_1:\,\alpha_1\neq 0, \alpha_2\neq 0,\alpha_3\neq 0,\alpha_4\neq 0,\alpha_5\neq 0\]

From the ANOVA table, the results of F test shows that null hypothesis test above should be rejected which means that all the independent variables in model1 have significant relationship with response variable(BL)

Build Models The process of build models, I summarize the information above 1. I won’t include year as my predictor 2. there are interaction between continents and GDP, and continents and year education in sense of impacts on IMR 3. log2(IMR) virtually have a linear relationship with year education 4. log(IMR) don’t have strong linear relationship with GDP 5. income class have virtually have significant relationship with IMR, the lower income class, the higher IMR

I start to build my models by explore the data, from one independent variable to two or three variables, if the variable does not have significant relationship, I will exclude this variable. from the plot I found that the average IMR decreases when GDP increase in what it looks to be a geometric decay, so I transformed GDP. The histogram of IMR skewed, so I try to use log2 to transform it, it worked which mean IMR is geometric data. I observed the interaction when i fix one variable and change another. Then I start from linear model and also add polynomial for non-linear variables, also, I try to use GAM and GLM that can accommodate non-linear relationship.

based on data information above, I try to build some model, i finally get three models that i this best. Model1: \[E[\log_{2}(\verb|infant_mortarity_rate|)|\verb|years_education|,\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|),\verb|continent|,\verb|income_class|]=\sigma_0 + \sigma_1\verb|years_education| + \sigma_2\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|) + \sigma_3\verb|continent|\\ + \sigma_4\verb|income_class|+\sigma_5\verb|continent|*\verb|income_class|\\ +\sigma_6\verb|years_education|*\verb|continent|*\verb|income_class|\]

Model2: \[E[\log_{2}(\verb|infant_mortarity_rate|)|\verb|years_education|,\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|),\verb|continent|,\verb|income_class|]=\beta_0 +\beta_1\verb|years_education| + \beta_2\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|) + \beta_3\verb|continent|\\ + \beta_4\verb|income_class|+\beta_5\verb|years_education|*\verb|continent|\\+ \beta_6\verb|continent|*\verb|income_class|\]

Model3: \[E[\log_{2}(\verb|infant_mortarity_rate|)|\verb|years_education|,\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|),\verb|continent|,\verb|income_class|]=\alpha_0 +\alpha_1\verb|continent| + s(\log_{10}(\verb|gdp|)) + s(\verb|years_education|)\]

There are AIC of three models

model_11<- lm(log2(infant_mortality_rate) ~ years_education + log10(gdp) + continent + income_class + continent*income_class + years_education*continent*income_class,   sdg)

model_22<- lm(log2(infant_mortality_rate) ~years_education + log10(gdp) + continent + income_class + years_education*continent + continent*income_class,   sdg)

model_33 <- gam(log2(infant_mortality_rate) ~ continent+s(years_education,k=4) + s(log10(gdp),k=4),data =sdg)
cat("AIC of Model1:",extractAIC(model_11)[2],"\n")

Hypothesis test

Hypothesis test for model1 \[H_0:\, \sigma_0=\sigma_1=\sigma_2=\sigma_3=\sigma_4=\sigma_5=\sigma_6=0\ \qquad \mbox{vs} \qquad H_1:\,\sigma_0\neq 0, \sigma_1\neq 0,\sigma_2\neq 0,\sigma_3\neq 0,\sigma_4\neq 0,\sigma_5\neq0,\sigma_6\neq0\] From the table of ANOVA, there is F test results, it shows that each coefficient is not equal 0, which means i should reject null hypothesis test above. Each predictors in my model have significant relationship with response variable(IMR)
